title: Kenny Elissonde's Pinarello Dogma F10 – Gallery
text:
Kenny Elissonde's Pinarello Dogma F10 – Gallery A detailed look at the Team Sky riders' bike for the upcoming season 1 / 23 Kenny Elissonde's Pinarello Dogma F10 (Josh Evans / Immediate Media) Continental Competiton 25mm tubular tyres are the most popular tyre in the WorldTour peloton (Josh Evans / Immediate Media) The aerodynamic tabs on the fork dropout are inspired from Bradley Wiggins Hour Record bike (Josh Evans / Immediate Media) A closer look at Shimano's Dura-Ace 9150 shifters (Josh Evans / Immediate Media) Team Sky use Elite Custom Race Plus bottle cages (Josh Evans / Immediate Media) Ellisonde's saddle is marked for ease of setup (Josh Evans / Immediate Media) A look at the cockpit (Josh Evans / Immediate Media) The F10 bottom bracket area (Josh Evans / Immediate Media) A look at the carbon construction of the saddle (Josh Evans / Immediate Media) The bike is equipped with a Dura-Ace 9000 crankset (Josh Evans / Immediate Media) Shimano Dura-Ace 9150 rear derailleur (Josh Evans / Immediate Media)   new derailleur (Josh Evans / Immediate Media) Shimano Dura-Ace 9150 front derailleur (Josh Evans / Immediate Media) The 9100 series crankset should arrive in time for the spring (Josh Evans / Immediate Media) The Frenchman's race number was cut to fit the frameset (Josh Evans / Immediate Media) A look at the Dura-Ace 9100 rear brake (Josh Evans / Immediate Media) Black on black Fizik Arione for Elissonde (Josh Evans / Immediate Media) Pinarello decals feature on the rear of the seattube (Josh Evans / Immediate Media) Skip Ad After Owain Doull fell ill ahead of the Tour Down Under, Team Sky flew in Kenny Elissonde at the eleventh hour to replace the Welshman for the WorldTour opener. Elissonde, who was training in Australia with Chris Froome during January, made it to Adelaide for the race start and worked as a domestique for team leader Sergio Henao. Related Articles The best of the London Bike Show 2017 – Gallery Pinarello unveiled the Dogma F10 last month and the bike is equipped with new aerodynamic features. The tabs on the rear of the fork dropouts are inspired by Bradley Wiggins' hour record bike and the concave downtube, inspired from the Bolide time trial frame, claims to reduce drag by 12.6 per cent versus the previous incarnation of the bike. Also on the downtube, Pinarello has introduced an E-Link system, which can charge and update the new Shimano Dura-Ace 9150 Di2 groupset. The bike features the latest electronic groupset components from Shimano, whilst the crankset and wheels remained Dura-Ace 9000 series due to a shortage of new cranks and a high enough quantity of wheelsets respectively. 
Ellisonde rides a size 44 frameset, 170mm cranks and a 112mm stem combined with narrow 380mm handlebars. The handlebar tape, handlebars and stem are all supplied by ONE components and the bike is complimented with an all black Fizik Arione saddle. Full Specifications 
Frame: Pinarello Dogma F10, size 44 Fork: Pinarello Onda F10 with ForkFlap Handlebar: PRO Vibe alloy, 380mm Stem: PRO Vibe alloy, 112mm Brakes: Shimano Dura-Ace 9100 Brake/shift levers: Shimano Dura-Ace 9150 Front derailleur: Shimano Dura-Ace 9150 Rear derailleur: Shimano Dura-Ace 9150 Cassette: Shimano Dura-Ace, 11-28T Cranks: Shimano Dura-Ace 9070, 53-39T Wheelset: Shimano Dura-Ace C50 Tyres: Continental Competition tubular, 25mm Seatpost: Pinarello Dogma F10 Bottle cages: Elite Custom Race Plus
